Introduction¶

Ford GoBike is a regional public bicycle sharing system in the San Francisco Bay Area, California. Beginning operation in August 2013 as Bay Area Bike Share, the Ford GoBike system currently has over 2,600 bicycles in 262 stations across San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose. On June 28, 2017, the system officially launched as Ford GoBike in a partnership with Ford Motor Company. After Motivate's acquisition by Lyft, the system was renamed to Bay Wheels in June 2019.

Ford GoBike, like other bike share systems, consists of a fleet of specially designed, sturdy and durable bikes that are locked into a network of docking stations throughout the city. The bikes can be unlocked from one station and returned to any other station in the system, making them ideal for one-way trips. The bikes are available for use 24 hours/day, 7 days/week, 365 days/year and riders have access to all bikes in the network when they become a member or purchase a pass.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores the Ford GoBike's trip data for public containing rides from Jan 2018 to Dec 2018.

Gathering data¶

Firstly, I saved all the csv files from the FordGoBike website in a folder. After this, I used the glob and os modules to combine all the files into a single file fordgobike.csv

In [12]:
path = r'C:\Users\Pradeep Gurunathan\FordGo_project_visualization\Data'
all_files = glob.glob(os.path.join(path, "*.csv"))
df = pd.concat((pd.read_csv(f) for f in all_files), ignore_index = True)
df.to_csv('fordgobike.csv', index = False)

Quality Issues¶

Before assessing the data for visualization, there are some quality issues that need to be cleaned.

  • The following columns are not in object format:
    • start_station_id
    • bike_id
    • end_station_id
  • Start/end times are not in the timestamp format.
  • Member birth is in the float format, but should be converted to integer format.
  • Member birthdates have a few inaccurate values(Dates prior to 1900).
  • User type, gender and bike_share_for_all_trip can be set to category format.
  • We can further enhance the dataset with more details extracted from Start time and end time like month, day, hour, weekday.
  • We can also calculate age of the user from user birth year for any further analysis.

Tidiness Issues¶

Before assessing the data for visualization, there are some tidiness issues that need to be cleaned.

  • Drop unnecessary Columns that are not used in our analysis
  • Dataset should be cleaned to form a Master Dataset future visualization purpose

Cleaning data¶

Cleaning the Gathered Data based assessment of data.

Before cleaning we are taking a copy of the data.

Define¶

Converting several of the columns to the appropriate data type:

  • Bike ID, start station ID, and end station ID to object format.
  • Starting and ending times to the timestamp format.
  • User type, gender, and bike share for all to category format.

Code¶

In [23]:
# Changing the format to datetime format
fordbikes_clean.start_time = pd.to_datetime(fordbikes_clean.start_time)
fordbikes_clean.end_time = pd.to_datetime(fordbikes_clean.end_time)
In [24]:
# Changing the user_type, member_gender, and bike_share_for_all_trip to category format
fordbikes_clean.user_type=fordbikes_clean.user_type.astype('category')
fordbikes_clean.member_gender = fordbikes_clean.member_gender.astype('category')
fordbikes_clean.bike_share_for_all_trip = fordbikes_clean.bike_share_for_all_trip.astype('category')
In [25]:
# Changing the bike_id, start_station_id, and end_station_id to object format
fordbikes_clean.bike_id = fordbikes_clean.bike_id.astype(str)
fordbikes_clean.start_station_id = fordbikes_clean.start_station_id.astype(str)
fordbikes_clean.end_station_id = fordbikes_clean.end_station_id.astype(str)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The data is straightforward to understand. This data has been collected efficiently, providing a valuable collection of data to work with and draw conclusions from.

This notebook uses data collected from January 2018 through December 2018. There were approximately 185,000 bike rides in the San Francisco Bay area of California, USA during this period.

The following dataset contained features about:

  • Trip Duration (seconds)
    • Start Time and Date
    • End Time and Date
  • Start Station Name
  • End Station Name
  • Bike ID
  • User Type
    • Member Year of Birth
    • Member Gender

After some cleaning, I enhanced the dataset with some features that I found necessary to perform interesting analysis.

  • Member age
  • Start Time Month
  • Start Time Month Number
  • Start Time Day of the Week
  • Start Time Hour
  • End Time Hour
  • Duration(in min)

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature of interest in this dataset according to me is the start and end times of the ride taken i.e. month/weekday/hour. With this data, we can forecast the demand of the bikes. Moreover, we have data related to the users such as age, gender, whether the user is a paying member/casual user. This user data can be used to decide which age group or gender group to target in marketing campaigns in order to drive business decisions.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think that start and end times related information will be exploited heavily for forecasting bike demand in my analysis. Along with the time based information, I will also use the customer related data such as age & gender to better understand the user-driven role behind each ride.

customer_prop = customer / fordgobikes_master['bike_id'].count()
subscriber_prop = subscriber / fordgobikes_master['bike_id'].count()

# Pie chart for user type
plt.figure(figsize=[10,5])

labels = ['Customer','Subscriber']
sizes = [customer_prop,subscriber_prop]
explode = (0,0.3)
colors = ['darkorange','steelblue']

plt.axis('equal')
plt.suptitle('Ford GoBike System - Customers vs. Subscribers', y=1.05, fontsize=14, fontweight='bold');

Observation: The bike sharing system is mainly used by subscribers (88%) than ocassional riders (12%).

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Due to the assessing & cleaning efforts, there weren't any suprises that I came across during the exploratory and visualization phases. There was one unusal points for the duration (sec), which in some cases lasted more than 24h. This was a unsual outlier that I didn't anticipate. For the histogram I set the max range to 3600 sec = 60 min.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There was one unusal distribution for the member birth year, which in some cases was dated before 1900. Since 99% of the members are between 20 and 67 years, I removed users older than 66 to make the data tidy.

So far, the data reveals that adults in the average working age range of 29 - 42 years are the primary user base for the system using the bikes on their daily work commutes.

# Let's set the weekday order
fordgobikes_master['start_time_weekday'] =  pd.Categorical(fordgobikes_master['start_time_weekday'], 
                                                categories=['Mon','Tue','Wed','Thu','Fri','Sat', 'Sun'], 
                                                ordered=True)
plt.figure(figsize=(9,8))
plt.suptitle('Ford GoBike System - Hourly usage throughout the week - Customers vs. Subscribers', y=1.05, fontsize=16, fontweight='bold');


#Plotting a heatmap for Customers
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
df_customer = fordgobikes_master.query('user_type == "Customer"').groupby(["start_time_hour", "start_time_weekday"])["bike_id"].size().reset_index()
df_customer = df_customer.pivot('start_time_hour','start_time_weekday','bike_id')
sns.heatmap(df_customer,cmap='BuPu')
plt.title("Customer", y=1.015, fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Weekday')
plt.ylabel('Start Time Hour');


#Plotting a heatmap for Subscribers
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
df_subscriber = fordgobikes_master.query('user_type == "Subscriber"').groupby(["start_time_hour", "start_time_weekday"])["bike_id"].size().reset_index()
df_subscriber = df_subscriber.pivot('start_time_hour','start_time_weekday','bike_id')
sns.heatmap(df_subscriber,cmap='BuPu')
plt.title("Subscriber", y=1.015, fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Weekday')
plt.ylabel('');

Observation: The plot perfectly summarizes the different trends altogether for customers and subscribers I was visualizing in the above plots.

Customers ride the FordGoBikes more often on weekends:

  • Weekdays(Mon-Fri): Most rides happen around 8-9am and 5-6pm with the peak on Fridays around 5pm.
  • Weekends(Sat-Sun): Most rides happen between 11am - 6pm with the peak on Saturdays around 1pm - 2pm.

Subscribers use the bike sharing system mostly on weekdays:

  • Weekdays(Mon-Fri): Most rides happen around 8-9am and 5-6pm with the peak on Tuesdays around 8am.
  • Weekends(Sat-Sun): The bikes are hardly rented during the weekends as most of them use the bikes for daily work commute.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

This section enhanced the previous topics of data exploration through different visuals and adding in more variables to compare to other variables. Plotting a heatmap of demand of the bikes throughout the day on a weekly basis shed a new light on the time based discussion on when and what time each user group uses the bike sharing system. Plotting the bike trips throughout the day and bike trips within the weekdays separately gave the impression that the demand for bikes is quite high throughout the day with a peak around 5pm which is not entirely true. The trend within weekdays for customers follows the one for subscribers who rent bikes mainly around commute hours (8-9am and 5-6pm). For customers, as depicted in bivariate explorations, most of the trips happen on weekends but mainly between 11am - 6pm with the peak on Saturdays around 2pm, what was previously not visible only possible through the multivariate exploration. By adding gender as the hue for each plot, we got a better understanding of the gender distribution for the usage of the FordGoBikes.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Nothing out of the blue here. It was interesting to note the sharp monthly difference for Males vs. Females vs. Other, and how close the Female count got to the Male Customer count in January through March. This may be a potential loss of possible Customers converting to Subscribers.Moreover Females take longer trips than Males and others.
